ion of Africans navigating the multiplicity of contemporary African life—a process that is augmented by globalized culture and the Internet. Keenly aware of the world outside Taita and Kenya, Ngeti dreams big, with endless plans for striking it rich. As he struggles to free himself from what he imagines to be the hold of the past, he embarks on an odyssey that takes him to local diviners, witch-finders, Pentecostal preachers, and prophets. This is the fascinating ethnography of Mwadime and Smith, largely told through their shared emails, journals, and recorded conversations in the field. Throughout, the reader is struck by the immediacy and poignancy of coauthor Ngeti's narrative, which marks a groundbreaking shift in the nature of anthropological fieldwork and writing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aTaita (African people)xReligious life. 0aTaita (African people)xSocial life and customs. 0aWitchcraftzKenyazTaita Hills. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  a21st century international relations.  aafrica.  aafrican studies.  aanthropology.  aconnectivity.  acultural anthropology.  acultural studies.  adiscussion books.  aengaging.  aethnographic research.  afriendship.  aglobal africa.  aglobalization.  ainternet.  ajournal entries.  akenya.  alively.  alocal diners.  amultiplicity of african life.  anew research project.  apentecostal preachers.  aprophets.  arealistic.  arecorded conversations.  aredemption.  areligion.  ashared emails.  asorcery.  atransnational.  awitch finders.  ayoung generation.1 aMwadime, Ngeti, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz97805202811034